
                                            The settlement follows the Competition Commission’s investigation into the collusive conduct of manufacturers which began in 2012. 
                                         JOHANNESBURG - Autoliv  has agreed to pay a penalty of almost R150 million for contravening the Competition Act. The manufacturer of airbags, seatbelts, and steering wheels has concluded a settlement agreement with the Competition Commission for its prohibited involvement in price fixing, market division and collusive tendering with competitors. The settlement follows the commission’s investigation into the collusive conduct of manufacturers which began in 2012. The commission's Sipho Ngwema says other companies are still being investigated. “We have been investigating the allegations. And the investigation had to be amended to include more companies. And this is the first company in terms of that investigation that has pleaded guilty to collusion and has agreed to pay a fine of R150 million.”